Thanks so much for coming along to this session today. It's a real honor and a

2
00:00:10,683 --> 00:00:15,244
privilege for me and Tameem to be here today. So I'm Dominic Matthews, I'm

3
00:00:15,304 --> 00:00:21,427
commercial director at Ninja Theory and I'm here with Tameem Antoniades who is

4
00:00:21,887 --> 00:00:26,589
one of the Ninja Theory co-founders and chief creative ninja at the studio. So

5
00:00:27,789 --> 00:00:31,711
today we're going to talk to you about Hellblade Senua's Sacrifice which has

6
00:00:31,731 --> 00:00:33,751
been an incredible journey for us.

7
00:00:35,470 --> 00:00:39,293
It's really great to be able to be here today to share that journey with you.

8
00:00:42,115 --> 00:00:46,299
Please remember to evaluate the session, particularly if you think it's good.

9
00:00:47,560 --> 00:00:50,062
If you don't think it's good, then don't bother.

10
00:00:52,464 --> 00:00:55,467
Cool, so we'll crack on with the presentation.

11
00:00:55,507 --> 00:00:57,629
So a bit about Ninja Theory first.

12
00:00:59,272 --> 00:01:01,613
We're a studio of about 100 people.

13
00:01:01,653 --> 00:01:03,094
We're based in Cambridge in the UK.

14
00:01:04,094 --> 00:01:07,195
And we've been making games for 18 years now.

15
00:01:09,976 --> 00:01:15,678
And over those years, we've created a number of titles,

16
00:01:15,698 --> 00:01:17,619
starting with Kung Fu Chaos back in 2003

17
00:01:17,979 --> 00:01:21,160
for the original Xbox with Microsoft,

18
00:01:21,901 --> 00:01:23,501
Heavenly Sword for the PlayStation 3 in 2007 with Sony.

19
00:01:26,731 --> 00:01:29,952
Enslaved Odyssey to the West in 2010 with Namco Bandai.

20
00:01:31,213 --> 00:01:34,174
DMC Devil May Cry, the reboot of that franchise in 2013.

21
00:01:34,814 --> 00:01:37,135
And then the definitive edition of that in 2015.

22
00:01:37,455 --> 00:01:43,458
And we worked on Disney Infinity 3.0 in 2015 as well.

23
00:01:43,498 --> 00:01:45,859
So we created the starter play set for that, as well as

24
00:01:46,319 --> 00:01:49,180
redesigning the entire combat system.

25
00:01:51,300 --> 00:01:56,587
And then the title in question, last year on August the 8th we released

26
00:01:57,168 --> 00:02:03,978
Hellblade Senua's Sacrifice, which was our first independently funded and self-published title.

27
00:02:06,718 --> 00:02:07,439
The game was sold at $29.99.

28
00:02:08,079 --> 00:02:12,482
It was a PS4 and PC only title, a digital only title.

29
00:02:13,843 --> 00:02:17,365
And it really focused on Ninja Theory DNA,

30
00:02:17,485 --> 00:02:20,047
that DNA that we've created over the last 15 years,

31
00:02:20,087 --> 00:02:24,369
which is really creating immersive worlds

32
00:02:24,509 --> 00:02:26,251
and character-led stories

33
00:02:27,631 --> 00:02:30,813
and visceral, fluid combat gameplay.

34
00:02:32,183 --> 00:02:37,087
and combining all of those things to create an experience that really is what we see as

35
00:02:37,147 --> 00:02:39,349
pure ninja theory for ninja theory fans.

36
00:02:41,431 --> 00:02:49,117
And it tells the story of Senua, a Celtic warrior, and her vision quest to find the

37
00:02:49,157 --> 00:02:55,082
soul of her lover, and it's a journey into psychosis, which, to me, we'll talk about

38
00:02:55,443 --> 00:02:56,043
a bit more later.

39
00:02:57,708 --> 00:03:00,349
But to kind of tell the Hellblade story from the beginning,

40
00:03:00,909 --> 00:03:01,890
we need to go back to 2014.

41
00:03:02,350 --> 00:03:06,971
We just released DMC Devil May Cry.

42
00:03:08,792 --> 00:03:12,593
And as a studio, we took a step back

43
00:03:13,133 --> 00:03:18,974
and took a look at the market at that time and the game space.

44
00:03:19,795 --> 00:03:25,436
We tried to pitch a very big AAA game to publishers.

45
00:03:27,019 --> 00:03:32,871
a game called Razor, which never, uh, was never greenlit. It was a big games as a service

46
00:03:32,911 --> 00:03:34,173
title. Um.

47
00:03:35,008 --> 00:03:40,651
And through that process, we really identified that the market had evolved into something

48
00:03:41,912 --> 00:03:53,857
where essentially middle tier, mid-sized developers like us making AAA games couldn't really survive.

49
00:03:53,877 --> 00:03:56,778
It was a difficult market for studios like us.

50
00:03:57,899 --> 00:03:59,179
This was really down to the...

51
00:04:01,828 --> 00:04:08,173
The AAA arms race as we see it, which is the fixed price of AAA games at retail of $60,

52
00:04:08,253 --> 00:04:18,140
has meant that developers and games can't compete on price and instead have to compete on size and

53
00:04:18,300 --> 00:04:25,405
scale and scope. And this has meant that over the years games have got bigger and bigger and bigger.

54
00:04:26,312 --> 00:04:28,872
Development teams have got bigger and bigger and bigger.

55
00:04:29,412 --> 00:04:31,413
And of course, development costs have got bigger and

56
00:04:31,433 --> 00:04:32,593
bigger and bigger too.

57
00:04:34,453 --> 00:04:38,874
And what that has meant is that many genres that have

58
00:04:39,275 --> 00:04:43,716
thrived in the AAA space in years gone by simply can't

59
00:04:43,796 --> 00:04:46,736
survive anymore because they can't appeal to enough people

60
00:04:46,816 --> 00:04:47,656
to be justified.

61
00:04:48,717 --> 00:04:53,158
Games at this level now need to appeal to not just 2

62
00:04:53,518 --> 00:04:55,538
million people or 3 million people.

63
00:04:56,719 --> 00:05:00,481
But now we're talking about 5, 6, 7, 8 million people.

64
00:05:02,002 --> 00:05:06,025
And through the process of us talking to publishers

65
00:05:06,465 --> 00:05:11,769
about this big title that we were looking at,

66
00:05:11,829 --> 00:05:17,413
and over the years we kind of came up with this checklist of tick boxes

67
00:05:17,513 --> 00:05:20,735
that titles now need to tick in order to survive in that space.

68
00:05:22,961 --> 00:05:26,642
Things like, what's the season pass gonna look like?

69
00:05:26,662 --> 00:05:28,542
Well, you need to have multiplayer.

70
00:05:28,582 --> 00:05:30,322
Every game needs to have multiplayer now.

71
00:05:30,842 --> 00:05:33,743
Well, does your protagonist appeal to enough people?

72
00:05:34,483 --> 00:05:39,144
Is it a Caucasian male with stubble and a shaved head?

73
00:05:39,204 --> 00:05:41,604
Because, hey, that's what everyone's looking for

74
00:05:41,664 --> 00:05:42,225
these days.

75
00:05:42,445 --> 00:05:43,685
Yeah, just like me, yeah.

76
00:05:43,905 --> 00:05:44,205
Sorry.

77
00:05:44,225 --> 00:05:44,885
Yeah.

78
00:05:46,885 --> 00:05:47,065
Yeah.

79
00:05:47,786 --> 00:05:48,446
Thank you to me.

80
00:05:52,833 --> 00:06:02,879
And this kind of checklist culture in the AAA space has sadly meant that many genres

81
00:06:04,460 --> 00:06:11,545
have disappeared at the AAA end, and unfortunately so too have the teams and the developers

82
00:06:11,645 --> 00:06:13,145
behind those types of games.

83
00:06:15,047 --> 00:06:17,508
And those developers have either disappeared altogether...

84
00:06:18,558 --> 00:06:22,519
They've had to move away from AAA development,

85
00:06:24,560 --> 00:06:26,541
or they've had to go and do something else

86
00:06:27,261 --> 00:06:28,182
completely different.

87
00:06:28,502 --> 00:06:30,823
And the list of studios that have disappeared

88
00:06:30,843 --> 00:06:32,964
between 2000 and 2017 is absolutely phenomenal.

89
00:06:42,250 --> 00:06:46,712
And it's genres of games that I loved playing when I was younger,

90
00:06:46,732 --> 00:06:50,293
like Jet Set Radio and Parappa the Rapper and Aiko and Okami,

91
00:06:50,813 --> 00:06:55,815
all incredible games, high production values, incredibly creative,

92
00:06:57,396 --> 00:07:01,257
but just not mainstream enough to appeal to those millions and millions of people.

93
00:07:02,810 --> 00:07:10,556
So for us as a studio, we felt that pinch in being in the situation where a team of

94
00:07:10,576 --> 00:07:15,279
a hundred people, we make games that people love.

95
00:07:17,340 --> 00:07:18,941
We've got a fan base behind us.

96
00:07:19,142 --> 00:07:23,184
It's not huge, but it's a dedicated fan base that love what we do.

97
00:07:24,265 --> 00:07:29,169
But we were left with this choice of do we either ramp up our team and our studio,

98
00:07:29,669 --> 00:07:35,313
triple our team size to make games that can appeal to those many, many, many millions of people

99
00:07:36,234 --> 00:07:42,158
and risk sacrificing our core values and our creativity, I think, in the process?

100
00:07:43,139 --> 00:07:48,322
Or do we walk away from our, at that time, 15 years of development in the console business?

101
00:07:49,984 --> 00:07:51,805
And we didn't want to do either of those things.

102
00:07:54,144 --> 00:07:57,806
And that situation I think can be kind of summed up in this slide, which is

103
00:07:59,928 --> 00:08:05,832
players want creative games, players want the kind of games that creative developers make,

104
00:08:05,892 --> 00:08:08,253
the games that we at Ninja Theory make.

105
00:08:09,034 --> 00:08:12,156
And frankly, that's what we want to make.

106
00:08:12,196 --> 00:08:15,638
We're in the business of making the games that we want to make for the people that want them.

107
00:08:16,537 --> 00:08:20,200
but there was a block on this, the AAA space wasn't allowing us to do that.

108
00:08:20,261 --> 00:08:24,704
So, we wanted to find another way.

109
00:08:24,724 --> 00:08:26,706
We didn't want to go big and we didn't want to go home.

110
00:08:26,746 --> 00:08:28,808
We wanted to find a third way.

111
00:08:31,470 --> 00:08:35,674
And we identified in the market that there's really these two extremes.

112
00:08:36,975 --> 00:08:38,236
On one side you have...

113
00:08:39,052 --> 00:08:44,293
independent games where creativity is incredible.

114
00:08:44,853 --> 00:08:47,174
New genres are being created all the time.

115
00:08:50,155 --> 00:08:54,956
But budgetary restrictions mean that quite often

116
00:08:55,516 --> 00:08:59,657
those small teams have to go down a route

117
00:08:59,697 --> 00:09:01,378
that isn't triple A production values.

118
00:09:02,718 --> 00:09:05,880
And then on the other side, in the blockbuster space,

119
00:09:06,921 --> 00:09:09,923
games are getting bigger, the production values are phenomenal,

120
00:09:10,724 --> 00:09:13,626
and it's just incredible what's being achieved there.

121
00:09:14,987 --> 00:09:21,251
But each of those games have to fit into very narrow genres,

122
00:09:22,012 --> 00:09:26,595
a small number of genres that can survive at that very top end.

123
00:09:27,256 --> 00:09:28,417
So these two extremes,

124
00:09:28,737 --> 00:09:31,639
but really nothing that sits in the middle of those two.

125
00:09:32,840 --> 00:09:36,221
And this is the space that we called Independent AAA.

126
00:09:36,981 --> 00:09:40,142
And Independent AAA was about making AAA quality games,

127
00:09:42,323 --> 00:09:45,204
but that can be offered at lower flexible pricing, so

128
00:09:45,244 --> 00:09:50,486
that we can break away from that $60 retail model, make a

129
00:09:50,546 --> 00:09:54,127
game that we want to make, that is the scale and the

130
00:09:54,247 --> 00:09:56,208
scope that we want to make, and then price it

131
00:09:56,248 --> 00:09:56,788
appropriately.

132
00:09:57,848 --> 00:10:00,071
It's about having creative ownership.

133
00:10:01,773 --> 00:10:05,496
The independent freedom gives you self-publishing so we can

134
00:10:05,556 --> 00:10:07,799
build a direct relationship with our players.

135
00:10:08,560 --> 00:10:12,003
And digital distribution is key to the model, too.

136
00:10:12,323 --> 00:10:15,967
It allows us to achieve higher margins per unit that we sell.

137
00:10:16,187 --> 00:10:17,068
It allows us to have

138
00:10:17,845 --> 00:10:23,947
price control, and it allows us to deliver our product to fans

139
00:10:24,187 --> 00:10:27,667
across the world, wherever they may be, without the need to

140
00:10:27,707 --> 00:10:31,788
have a huge sales and publishing and distribution

141
00:10:31,828 --> 00:10:34,249
team within our small studio.

142
00:10:37,009 --> 00:10:41,030
So this started out as a concept for how we could break

143
00:10:41,090 --> 00:10:44,591
through that AAA block, make AAA production.

144
00:10:46,235 --> 00:10:51,598
gains with AAA production values, but with a small team and with a small budget.

145
00:10:51,658 --> 00:10:54,840
So fundamentally, how did this change things for us?

146
00:10:54,940 --> 00:11:00,102
Well, the biggest thing is that we were looking at a far smaller budget than we'd worked with

147
00:11:01,043 --> 00:11:01,523
ever before.

148
00:11:01,923 --> 00:11:07,406
So this isn't indie budgets.

149
00:11:07,446 --> 00:11:10,628
This is something bigger than that, but it's certainly something far smaller than...

150
00:11:11,967 --> 00:11:13,927
We would normally work with for a AAA game,

151
00:11:14,107 --> 00:11:16,208
and certainly far smaller than other AAA games

152
00:11:16,268 --> 00:11:19,269
are being made for in the current market.

153
00:11:21,669 --> 00:11:23,070
And the biggest cost in game development

154
00:11:23,130 --> 00:11:24,670
is obviously your team.

155
00:11:25,150 --> 00:11:29,832
So for us, we have a team of 100 people across Ninja Theory,

156
00:11:30,152 --> 00:11:31,972
and traditionally all of those people

157
00:11:31,992 --> 00:11:33,533
have worked on one product.

158
00:11:34,493 --> 00:11:37,454
But with Hellblade, we had a team of 20 people

159
00:11:37,754 --> 00:11:39,555
on the project across three years.

160
00:11:41,565 --> 00:11:46,008
So that meant that in many discipline areas, we had one person.

161
00:11:47,649 --> 00:11:52,251
And we had to have, we had to be very innovative, and we had to be very creative in the way

162
00:11:52,291 --> 00:11:56,854
in which we could deliver the quality and the quantity that we needed to, to make the

163
00:11:56,914 --> 00:12:00,816
experience that we had the vision for in Hellblade.

164
00:12:02,877 --> 00:12:04,398
And key to this really was...

165
00:12:05,839 --> 00:12:10,522
having the mindset and the attitude that we would never sacrifice on quality

166
00:12:11,363 --> 00:12:13,925
and it wasn't a question of can we do it, it was a question of

167
00:12:14,405 --> 00:12:14,965
how do we do it.

168
00:12:16,669 --> 00:12:19,932
and a good example of that is in performance capture.

169
00:12:20,532 --> 00:12:23,694
So performance capture is a technology and a technique

170
00:12:23,754 --> 00:12:27,517
that we've worked with since Heavenly Sword.

171
00:12:27,577 --> 00:12:29,238
It was a technology that we pioneered

172
00:12:29,278 --> 00:12:30,499
on that project in video games.

173
00:12:31,840 --> 00:12:34,922
And it's something that we strongly believe

174
00:12:35,282 --> 00:12:37,024
is the way in which you can realize

175
00:12:37,064 --> 00:12:40,126
the truest character performance in a game.

176
00:12:41,087 --> 00:12:42,967
So on Hellblade, when we started the project,

177
00:12:43,548 --> 00:12:45,808
we knew that this was something that we wanted to

178
00:12:46,229 --> 00:12:47,869
not just utilize in Hellblade,

179
00:12:47,929 --> 00:12:50,030
but that we wanted to push further

180
00:12:50,330 --> 00:12:52,331
and try and push the boundaries of what we could achieve,

181
00:12:53,011 --> 00:12:54,292
but with our very small budget.

182
00:12:54,332 --> 00:12:58,273
So typically we would fly out to the US or to New Zealand

183
00:12:59,234 --> 00:13:02,415
to a purpose-built motion capture facility

184
00:13:02,935 --> 00:13:06,937
to shoot all of the scenes for our games.

185
00:13:08,231 --> 00:13:10,992
But with Hellblade that just wasn't possible within our budget.

186
00:13:11,072 --> 00:13:16,314
So the solution that we came up with was certainly the idea initially was,

187
00:13:16,834 --> 00:13:19,515
well we've got our boardroom in the studio, which is our biggest meeting room.

188
00:13:20,856 --> 00:13:25,718
What about if we try and convert our boardroom into a motion capture studio?

189
00:13:26,899 --> 00:13:29,320
And initially those conversations were quite difficult internally,

190
00:13:29,360 --> 00:13:32,041
it was like, well, we still need to use it as a meeting room.

191
00:13:32,121 --> 00:13:33,621
It's like, okay, you can still have a table in there.

192
00:13:36,344 --> 00:13:38,647
Over time that table was moved out.

193
00:13:38,767 --> 00:13:43,113
But I think it's a good example of our attitude, which was,

194
00:13:43,133 --> 00:13:43,874
well, let's give it a go.

195
00:13:44,596 --> 00:13:47,219
Let's try and take a risk on this, and let's try and make

196
00:13:47,279 --> 00:13:48,401
it work, and if it doesn't, we'll move

197
00:13:48,441 --> 00:13:49,282
on to another solution.

198
00:13:50,704 --> 00:13:56,808
uh, we, uh, we went into that boardroom, um, uh, Balash, who's, uh, the cinematic lead on, on

199
00:13:56,928 --> 00:14:02,332
Hellblade, he, he drove to Ikea and bought wardrobe poles to mount our cameras on. We bought,

200
00:14:02,532 --> 00:14:07,936
um, uh, lighting from Amazon, so the light, the lights you can see in this, uh, video are, um,

201
00:14:08,536 --> 00:14:13,920
ceiling tile lights for, for offices from Amazon and they cost, uh, $50, $50 each, something in

202
00:14:13,940 --> 00:14:14,580
that kind of region.

203
00:14:15,441 --> 00:14:18,682
We bought soundproofing curtains, we bought gym mats for the floor,

204
00:14:19,502 --> 00:14:25,163
and we worked with Vicon to try and find a solution and a way to have a camera set up

205
00:14:25,203 --> 00:14:26,884
that would work within our budget.

206
00:14:27,904 --> 00:14:33,606
And that turned out to be the space in which we shot all of our cinematics for Hellblade.

207
00:14:33,626 --> 00:14:38,527
So every scene that you see in Hellblade was shot in our boardroom in this room.

208
00:14:40,746 --> 00:14:47,110
And an important point on this is that the quality of the data that we gained from this

209
00:14:47,330 --> 00:14:50,952
was in line, if not better than anything we'd achieved before.

210
00:14:51,293 --> 00:14:56,896
And that's the important point, is that we weren't just, we weren't, the important point

211
00:14:56,976 --> 00:15:02,080
is that what comes across on screen is not in any way compromised.

212
00:15:02,860 --> 00:15:04,581
If it was, we wouldn't have done this.

213
00:15:05,337 --> 00:15:08,700
was trying to find a way that we could do it within our, within our budget and keep that

214
00:15:08,740 --> 00:15:15,184
quality bar not just high but higher than it's ever been before for us at Ninja Theory. Um, so

215
00:15:15,204 --> 00:15:20,348
for comparison, um, obviously the cost we, that we had here were a fraction of what it cost for

216
00:15:20,408 --> 00:15:24,691
us to, um, you know, fly everyone out for a dedicated shoot. Uh, so, um, we, we, we, we

217
00:15:26,229 --> 00:15:30,613
But we built our own in-house mocap space for what it would cost

218
00:15:30,633 --> 00:15:33,336
for around three or four days in an external studio.

219
00:15:34,077 --> 00:15:37,420
So it gave us quality, but it also gave us a huge amount of flexibility,

220
00:15:37,841 --> 00:15:41,084
and flexibility that we now wouldn't want to give up moving forward.

221
00:15:41,605 --> 00:15:52,211
So not only did we use this for all of our cinematics, but also it was a tool that our animators could use to go into that space at any time they wanted, jump in a mocap suit and try stuff out.

222
00:15:52,251 --> 00:15:55,493
So throughout Hellblade, there's a lot of...

223
00:15:57,174 --> 00:16:01,115
a lot of detailed animation that Senua has in particular situations,

224
00:16:01,215 --> 00:16:03,235
so running through fire where she's coughing,

225
00:16:04,055 --> 00:16:06,016
balancing across beams,

226
00:16:06,096 --> 00:16:11,497
trying to visualize her different states of being within the game.

227
00:16:11,537 --> 00:16:13,617
So hundreds and hundreds of animations that we have in there.

228
00:16:13,637 --> 00:16:15,237
And that was really only possible because

229
00:16:15,738 --> 00:16:17,298
just along the corridor in our boardroom

230
00:16:17,318 --> 00:16:19,618
was a facility that our animators could go and use

231
00:16:20,038 --> 00:16:21,819
and they could experiment to try and find

232
00:16:22,619 --> 00:16:24,699
solutions to deliver that quality and detail

233
00:16:24,719 --> 00:16:26,840
that we needed to tell Senua's story.

234
00:16:28,788 --> 00:16:31,510
We also used that space for all of our VO recording.

235
00:16:32,810 --> 00:16:35,891
And again, this was something that was incredibly

236
00:16:35,911 --> 00:16:36,612
experimental.

