00:24:17,291 --> 00:24:23,917
So I always get asked what gave you the idea to do Hellblade.

375
00:24:24,737 --> 00:24:27,000
And when I think of truly original fantasy,

376
00:24:27,040 --> 00:24:29,342
I think of Lord of the Rings, 1984, Blade Runner,

377
00:24:29,982 --> 00:24:30,863
Night of the Living Dead.

378
00:24:30,943 --> 00:24:34,987
Obviously, fantasy goes way further back, Gilgamesh

379
00:24:35,027 --> 00:24:36,949
and Beowulf, what have you.

380
00:24:37,953 --> 00:24:44,978
I'd say most popular fantasy today is a derivation of those popular movies or books.

381
00:24:45,958 --> 00:24:53,923
And I didn't want to do that because they also come with their own set of rules and

382
00:24:53,963 --> 00:24:57,786
baggage and expectations that have been built up over time.

383
00:24:59,707 --> 00:25:01,748
So I really did want to make something original.

384
00:25:02,846 --> 00:25:06,169
a game that wasn't derived from those well-trodden tropes,

385
00:25:06,510 --> 00:25:08,492
and to find something that felt a bit more grounded.

386
00:25:09,933 --> 00:25:14,537
And I thought, fantasy comes from the mind, so why not go to the source?

387
00:25:15,278 --> 00:25:20,283
And a frightening, a very frightening and extreme example of what the mind

388
00:25:20,503 --> 00:25:24,847
is capable of creating can be found in psychotic mental illness.

389
00:25:26,192 --> 00:25:31,593
And at the time it sounded dangerous, perhaps even reckless, to broach that subject.

390
00:25:32,354 --> 00:25:39,276
But I do truly believe that the power of fantasy comes from its ability to help further understanding through allegory.

391
00:25:40,636 --> 00:25:44,737
A fantasy is able to break down prejudices and assumptions,

392
00:25:45,458 --> 00:25:50,259
because you have to open your mind to these worlds in order to accept and enjoy them.

393
00:25:52,389 --> 00:25:55,374
So the idea was born that Hellblade would be a classic hero's journey,

394
00:25:55,414 --> 00:25:59,341
but one where the fantasy world is a construct of Senua's mind.

395
00:25:59,361 --> 00:26:00,863
So that's sort of where it began.

396
00:26:07,900 --> 00:26:10,601
So just to cover what psychosis is,

397
00:26:12,602 --> 00:26:15,963
psychosis is a set of other symptoms

398
00:26:16,003 --> 00:26:17,584
and it can be caused by various causes,

399
00:26:19,045 --> 00:26:20,905
smoking pot, schizophrenia,

400
00:26:21,005 --> 00:26:22,886
you know, there's a multitude of causes.

401
00:26:24,086 --> 00:26:27,468
But it's about losing contact with reality

402
00:26:27,508 --> 00:26:31,329
and it often manifests itself with visions and voices

403
00:26:31,549 --> 00:26:33,130
and strange beliefs and delusions.

404
00:26:38,171 --> 00:26:39,031
Oh, excuse me.

405
00:26:45,354 --> 00:26:50,516
So, Senua can be described as having a severe psychotic mental illness.

406
00:26:51,176 --> 00:26:53,837
And it is a subject that is taboo for sure.

407
00:26:54,337 --> 00:27:00,180
And where it does feature, it's usually in the form of like the serial killer, you know,

408
00:27:00,300 --> 00:27:03,481
or the plot twist at the end where nothing was real, it was all a dream.

409
00:27:03,581 --> 00:27:05,042
Ah ha ha! You know, that's the, you know.

410
00:27:06,022 --> 00:27:06,502
I find that...

411
00:27:06,892 --> 00:27:09,215
both those aspects quite frustrating.

412
00:27:10,176 --> 00:27:13,100
So why is it not represented directly in more honesty in fiction?

413
00:27:13,821 --> 00:27:16,884
I think for one, we don't actually know

414
00:27:16,904 --> 00:27:19,647
a lot about it from a scientific point of view.

415
00:27:20,509 --> 00:27:24,774
Compared to physical illnesses and conditions, we're way behind when it

416
00:27:24,794 --> 00:27:26,015
comes to mental conditions.

417
00:27:27,099 --> 00:27:30,161
I mean, we're not taught about, if you think about it, we're not taught about the mind

418
00:27:30,221 --> 00:27:33,583
like in school, like we are taught about biology.

419
00:27:33,663 --> 00:27:38,225
So we all grow up ignorant about what the mind is, how it functions.

420
00:27:40,133 --> 00:27:45,515
I also think that a lot of creators think that this is dangerous territory.

421
00:27:45,815 --> 00:27:50,396
It's a Pandora's box that once opened will open you up to savage critical attacks

422
00:27:51,617 --> 00:27:53,037
that will expose your ignorance.

423
00:27:54,298 --> 00:27:57,179
This is something that I very much feared at the start of the project.

424
00:27:57,259 --> 00:28:01,820
I have no qualms with admitting that I was ignorant on the subject.

425
00:28:05,435 --> 00:28:08,556
And if you were around for DMC, you'd know that, like, you know,

426
00:28:09,057 --> 00:28:13,919
savage critical attacks is something we've sort of had to deal with before.

427
00:28:13,959 --> 00:28:17,941
So we weren't that afraid of dealing that if it would come.

428
00:28:19,942 --> 00:28:24,024
But creatively, what excited me was it was a path least trodden.

429
00:28:24,345 --> 00:28:28,287
I mean, I think that's what I was looking for.

430
00:28:28,367 --> 00:28:31,468
Just something different, something new, a chance to.

431
00:28:33,173 --> 00:28:37,354
show you what it might be like to experience the world through the mind of someone who

432
00:28:37,414 --> 00:28:38,555
experiences psychosis.

433
00:28:40,795 --> 00:28:46,477
It felt interesting, intellectually exciting, creatively, but I had to learn.

434
00:28:46,637 --> 00:28:47,758
The whole team had to learn.

435
00:28:50,119 --> 00:28:50,859
So how did we learn?

436
00:28:51,359 --> 00:28:58,221
Well, Dom went to Google and found Paul Fletcher, professor of health neuroscience and psychiatrist

437
00:28:58,241 --> 00:29:00,902
at the University of Cambridge, and sent him an email.

438
00:29:02,108 --> 00:29:08,714
He also got in touch with Wellcome, Wellcome Trust, which is a massive charity organization

439
00:29:09,155 --> 00:29:17,823
that deals with health. And they've often, Wellcome often provides grants for like arts

440
00:29:17,843 --> 00:29:24,929
projects and films, so we were hoping that, you know, with these, with their assistance,

441
00:29:25,009 --> 00:29:26,471
you know, they could open doors for us.

442
00:29:28,052 --> 00:29:34,135
So Paul and representatives of Wellcome met us, grilled us.

443
00:29:34,596 --> 00:29:37,237
We had to do a good amount of presentations to them.

444
00:29:38,158 --> 00:29:40,999
And once they came on board, they

445
00:29:41,019 --> 00:29:43,801
came on board fully for the full three years of development.

446
00:29:44,982 --> 00:29:49,004
They involved other clinicians and experts, Professor Charles

447
00:29:49,044 --> 00:29:52,867
Fernyhugh, an expert in voice hearing, lots of people

448
00:29:52,907 --> 00:29:55,288
with lived experience of psychosis.

449
00:29:56,809 --> 00:30:02,692
from Recovery College East in Cambridge and the Voice Collective, various other researchers and advisors.

450
00:30:03,412 --> 00:30:07,074
So they didn't just open doors, they really did blow the doors off.

451
00:30:08,295 --> 00:30:09,596
And I really would like to share what...

452
00:30:10,637 --> 00:30:14,259
the insights that we've had on this, because I think it's important, not just from a game

453
00:30:14,279 --> 00:30:21,442
development point of view, I think it's just a fascinating subject, so I'm sorry if it's

454
00:30:21,822 --> 00:30:24,123
slightly off the game developer's track.

455
00:30:24,983 --> 00:30:31,465
But this key insight that I learned, which is that we only really see the shadows of

456
00:30:31,525 --> 00:30:34,266
reality, is what underpins the whole of...

457
00:30:35,076 --> 00:30:37,199
the creative efforts in Hellblade.

458
00:30:37,839 --> 00:30:41,103
We like to think that we are objective, seeing the world as it is, but

459
00:30:41,824 --> 00:30:45,108
we are so far removed from objective reality that the whole concept

460
00:30:45,608 --> 00:30:46,790
is almost meaningless.

461
00:30:47,771 --> 00:30:49,813
And of course this is not a particularly new insight,

462
00:30:50,955 --> 00:30:53,538
as attested by Plato's allegory of the cave.

463
00:30:54,897 --> 00:30:57,939
And for those who are not familiar, the idea is that a bunch of people are in a cave

464
00:30:58,600 --> 00:31:03,184
and they're set up such that they can only see the projected shadows of people in the real world.

465
00:31:04,245 --> 00:31:08,829
And so they form their own strange interpretation of how this world functions

466
00:31:10,091 --> 00:31:14,715
until one of them breaks free and then sees the real world and then rushes back and tells them what it actually is like.

467
00:31:14,755 --> 00:31:18,518
And of course they think he's insane. It doesn't make sense to any of them.

468
00:31:20,760 --> 00:31:21,081
And so...

469
00:31:23,527 --> 00:31:25,328
This insight really does apply to us.

470
00:31:25,408 --> 00:31:27,369
I mean, we only see shadows.

471
00:31:27,389 --> 00:31:29,190
I mean, if you consider vision, light

472
00:31:29,270 --> 00:31:33,292
is a narrow spectrum of the electromagnetic spectrum.

473
00:31:33,832 --> 00:31:36,694
It's actually a 10 trillionth of the electromagnetic spectrum.

474
00:31:36,734 --> 00:31:41,216
That's how we define color and objects and concepts like race.

475
00:31:41,376 --> 00:31:43,317
Like we create our own reality just

476
00:31:43,337 --> 00:31:48,520
from that sliver of what we see out there in the universe.

477
00:31:49,829 --> 00:31:52,069
And we don't even experience the world in real time.

