00:31:52,109 --> 00:31:54,270
So from the time you click your fingers

479
00:31:54,350 --> 00:31:56,170
to understanding what you've just done

480
00:31:56,230 --> 00:31:58,211
or what you've just seen can take half a second.

481
00:31:58,871 --> 00:32:01,711
And our visual processing and our auditory processing

482
00:32:01,971 --> 00:32:03,711
happens at different speeds, so it's not in sync.

483
00:32:03,791 --> 00:32:06,352
So somehow our brain just manages

484
00:32:06,412 --> 00:32:10,333
to amass all this noisy, unreliable information

485
00:32:10,433 --> 00:32:13,793
and create a reality for us so that we can function.

486
00:32:20,754 --> 00:32:26,058
So, we feel like we are in a world that is fully 3D present with us at the center

487
00:32:26,078 --> 00:32:27,359
and we call this objective reality.

488
00:32:27,379 --> 00:32:31,243
And our mind is able to construct this fallacy of objectivity,

489
00:32:31,263 --> 00:32:33,145
a simulation of the world no less,

490
00:32:33,645 --> 00:32:36,588
based on everything we have experienced since birth.

491
00:32:37,268 --> 00:32:41,392
So, if you have wondered whether you are living in a simulation,

492
00:32:41,892 --> 00:32:43,774
I think one answer has to be yes.

493
00:32:44,014 --> 00:32:46,416
We are living in a simulation of our own mind's making.

494
00:32:49,117 --> 00:32:50,358
And so what does this mean?

495
00:32:53,579 --> 00:32:56,040
It means that we don't passively perceive a world.

496
00:32:56,760 --> 00:32:59,121
We don't just receive a world and our eyes see it.

497
00:32:59,201 --> 00:33:00,782
We actually hallucinate the world.

498
00:33:00,822 --> 00:33:02,503
In our every day, every second of every day,

499
00:33:02,583 --> 00:33:05,084
we are actually hallucinating a simulation of a world

500
00:33:05,484 --> 00:33:06,765
that our brain creates for us.

501
00:33:08,097 --> 00:33:13,239
Just think of moments when you were fearful at night and maybe you could see shapes and

502
00:33:13,279 --> 00:33:18,102
shadows or when you're really angry and you're red with rage, how you interpret what people

503
00:33:18,162 --> 00:33:21,503
say or the kind of grey lethargic world of grief.

504
00:33:21,663 --> 00:33:28,226
I mean these are all, the world looks different depending on how, on your state of mind.

505
00:33:32,601 --> 00:33:36,625
So in this context, it becomes easier to conceive of scenarios where our mind, with its endless

506
00:33:36,665 --> 00:33:40,529
adaptive feedback loops, can divert from the standard we term normality.

507
00:33:40,989 --> 00:33:46,595
And what we see in a psychotic mind is often a deconstruction, a separation of the fundamental

508
00:33:46,635 --> 00:33:51,720
relationships between sight, sound, senses, concepts, belief, even flow of time.

509
00:33:53,121 --> 00:33:56,962
And once we understood and accepted that we do not see through our eyes,

510
00:33:57,022 --> 00:33:59,523
but create worlds through our mind's eye,

511
00:33:59,803 --> 00:34:03,084
we had a model of reality that we could then start to deconstruct.

512
00:34:04,024 --> 00:34:07,386
And combined with the real lived experiences of people with psychosis,

513
00:34:08,046 --> 00:34:12,387
we had a powerful coming together of science, art, and human experience.

514
00:34:13,407 --> 00:34:16,268
So this was the eureka moment for me, the mind's eye.

515
00:34:16,328 --> 00:34:18,129
But what does this mean practically?

516
00:34:20,887 --> 00:34:24,631
It means we are not seeing this game through the lens of a cameraman.

517
00:34:24,991 --> 00:34:27,273
It means we're not hearing the music from the composer

518
00:34:27,674 --> 00:34:29,876
or seeing the editor's handiwork in the cutscenes.

519
00:34:30,977 --> 00:34:32,859
Everything has to feel subjective,

520
00:34:33,160 --> 00:34:37,144
as it would feel, look and sound to Senua through Hermione's eye.

521
00:34:39,762 --> 00:34:46,367
We like to think that we experience the world almost like a high definition photograph as it really is.

522
00:34:46,447 --> 00:34:52,351
But actually a lot of the time what we're doing is using what we already know to shape and govern what we perceive.

523
00:34:52,652 --> 00:34:55,754
You know, if we recognize that principle of how the brain functions,

524
00:34:55,814 --> 00:35:00,637
it may be that we can begin to understand what happens in the context of psychosis,

525
00:35:00,697 --> 00:35:06,041
because psychosis can't really easily be understood as just some malfunction of the mind.

526
00:35:06,101 --> 00:35:09,083
It's actually a very creative process where somebody constructs a world.

527
00:35:10,634 --> 00:35:16,480
So that's Professor Paul Fletcher, who I consider a mentor and guru

